@laynemorgan Now there's conflict-- both Kory & the daughter, Marigold, had misconceptions re: each other & misunderstandings of urban & rural life. Fear for their own communities & the world around them. How do you find truth in a world turned upside-down? We built everything out from there.

@laynemorgan Our lead character grew from that -- we created Kory Hernadez from Queens & sent her to live in a small town in Illinois. The family who took her in were the only ones willing to accept a stranger into their home -- their teenage daughter & others in the town weren't as accepting

@laynemorgan How would those places protect the most vulnerable? What if they had a program like "Pied Piper," the WWII initiative where children and vulnerable people were sent to the countryside to protect them from the blitz in London? That could be the inciting incident for the character.

@laynemorgan I often look to science & history (as human behavior repeats itself) to build out my world. In a situation like that, I thought war would probably break out in areas that had supply issues. Probably the more population-dense coasts, & modeled the experiences off modern-day war.

@laynemorgan Our podcast ANOMALY started as a fact in an encyclopedia of weird facts. It talked about what would probably happen if the poles shifted places -- it's possible, but not very probable -- but I thought that was cool. So...what if that happened? How would the world react?

PS As more and more people embrace an alcohol-free lifestyle, more and more companies are creating tasty NA options which means I can still have a great IPA without the effect of alcohol (shout out to @DrinkPartake, my NA beer of choice). 10/10

The past four years have been a rollercoaster, but I'm glad to have done it with a clear head as I continue to learn and grow. I'm not advocating for everyone to stop drinking or anything -- you do you -- but it was definitely the best choice for me. 9/10

As I gained clarity about how I was functioning in the world, I finally got an official ADHD diagnosis, my life (past and present) all started making sense, and I have started to learn how to create a better environment for me to work and live in. 8/10

Since then, I've continued to focus on my professional & personal development. I started @cerealmade with @hbnuss, am in development on a number of TV projects, had a feature film on @netflix, a podcast in @tribeca & @weare_thegotham, & worked in my first TV writers' room. 7/10

After cutting alcohol, I wrote regularly in the morning before work instead of working in fits and starts (no more hangovers as an excuse!). Within 9 months of going alcohol-free, I got into the @cfccreates Prime Time TV program, quit my day job, and began writing full-time. 6/10
It doesn't stop me from going to bars or parties or celebrating. I drink what I want to drink and you drink what you want to drink and we're all happy. 5/10
By cutting out alcohol, I sleep a lot better (which really helps me manage my ADHD) and wake up hangover-free. I have better focus, fewer lost nights, and more productive days. 4/10
As my brain is built to be very all or nothing -- moderation has not been a part of my vocabulary for most of my life so eliminating alcohol completely has been the best choice for me. 3/10

Alcohol is something that's easy to hide behind, to blame your choices, or lack of choices, on. As someone with ADHD, I've come to learn that alcohol can loosen my inhibitions and allow my impulsive side to take the front seat. 2/10

Today marks 4 years alcohol-free. New Years Day 2018, I just decided I didn't want to drink anymore. In that time, I think my life has become infinitely better both personally and professionally. 1/10

@LeonThomasBraun @jeannevb @RadenMara Getting some good solid samples in the genre/ tone of what you want to write on is key. #scriptchat
@LeonThomasBraun @jeannevb @RadenMara I just googled "books on tv writers rooms" -- there's a bunch of others on there, too. #scriptchat
@KieraHarvell Everyone in the room contributes to everything -- the showrunner makes the final call. #scriptchat

@LeonThomasBraun @jeannevb @RadenMara I'd also watch/ read interviews with TV writers as every room is a bit different. There are some books on Amazon re: writer's rooms (like this one: https://t.co/GO24inSKvB) or check out Shonda Rhimes masterclass #scriptchat

@LeonThomasBraun @jeannevb @RadenMara Then you outline (20 pages -- w/ sluglines) in 7 days, then revise according to notes, then go to script with usually 2 weeks to write. Some rooms will have notes sessions in the room, but on short orders, usually just showrunner/ network notes. #scriptchat

@LeonThomasBraun @jeannevb @RadenMara In my last room, we started by breaking storylines for characters over the season, then we did the plot for the full season, then broke episode by episode, around 5 days each episode. #scriptchat

@LeonThomasBraun @jeannevb @RadenMara To build a room, prod cos will reach out to agents looking for writers or showrunners will have writers they want to work with. They will read scripts, invite a select few to an interview, and create a room of people of varying levels of experience & backgrounds. #scriptchat

@jeannevb Before I even break my feature or pilot, I break down similar pilots or feature scripts so I can see the flow/ beats/ intersecting storylines/ how characters are introduced, etc. #scriptchat

@jeannevb I break the script in Miro or post-it notes on my wall (all broken into acts). Then I do a detailed outline (18 - 25 pages) with sluglines. It allows me to get the flow of the story without being seduced by dialogue. I allow myself to adjust wherever it's not working #scriptchat

A huge thanks to my execs Marianne & Sarah @MarVistaEnt and Marley from Neshama Entertainment. They gave amazing notes and really helped shepherd LETHAL LOVE, the fun sexy thrillery romp that comes out today! I hope you enjoy it! #LethalLove 12/12

The biggest hurdle was containing kissing to 2 locations that could be filmed at the end of the shoot to limit close contact time between the leads. I thought it'd be easy, but they kissed everywhere! So there was definitely some creativity that came into play. #LethalLove 11/12

I also had to contend w/ COVID protocols when writing my second draft -- we had to limit groups of people so scenes moved to before shops opened and after they closed. Scenes also moved to more open spaces, so it killed my dream of Blaine living that #vanlife. #LethalLove 10/12

As LETHAL LOVE is set in a bakery, I had a blast adding baked goods that were right for each part of the story -- sticky buns when we first meet the love interest, cherry pie when they get their flirt on, angry bread kneading...And the art department DELIVERED! #LethalLove 9/12

I dug into Lifetime & 90s thrillers with great recommendations from Josh Van Houdt & @MegElizHoops (a WEALTH of info!). The Hand That Rocks the Cradle was the biggest influence on Blaine's journey & it really helped ramp up the tension throughout LETHAL LOVE. #LethalLove 8/12

Once the outline was complete, I moved to draft. I originally tried to hide who the antagonist was from the audience until the midpoint. It wasn't working the way I thought, & when the execs suggested having his intentions out in the open, it broke open the film. #LethalLove 7/12

I asked them upfront the number of locations and characters (this is budget dependent so very important) so I went into the breaking and outlining process with this in mind. It was IMMENSELY helpful to know that going in. #LethalLove 6/12

We started working on the script in April and finished it in August. Lifetime-esque thrillers are written with a 9 act structure, and the team provided me with some sample outlines to follow as well as some links to some thrillers they just completed. #LethalLove 5/12

The exec loved the script and said she'd keep me in mind for future projects. In February 2020, she sent over a two-pager feature idea and asked if I'd be interested in writing it. Music, baking, complicated family relationships, and murder?? I WAS IN! #LethalLove 4/12

Sometime in October of 2019, that same exec went on the Ink Canada Facebook group (run by the wonderful @inkcanada) asking for horror/thriller writers. I reached back out to her and sent a sample horror feature (always be prepared!) #LethalLove 3/12

In June 2019, I met with an exec from Neshama Entertainment when I was at @BanffMedia as part of the LIFE-CHANGING (!!) @CorusPR Writer's Apprentice Program -- we had a great chat and I said I'd send her some of my work (I did). #LethalLove 2/12

@JazzBeeP For my last show (one hour drama), 5 days to break the episode, 5-7 days to write a 20-page outline, 24-hour turnaround on notes, 7 days on the script -- all done outside of the writer's room. Coffee is key! #scriptchat

@jeannevb @Tribeca Strategy is key. I think a lot about what I've written, what I want to write, and why that's key to do now. Timing is crucial. Also, how will it help me move the needle on staffing or getting meetings (and hopefully selling). Lots to think about #scriptchat

@collinlieberg @jeannevb @Tribeca The hungriest mouth gets fed -- paying jobs always come first, but I'll slowly chip away at my own stuff on the side. Like right now -- room finished 3 weeks ago, and my new pilot is ready to go to producers so I can shift to that. #scriptchat

@P_Hendrickson Feature writing/ spec writing can be very solo...at first...but unless you are making it yourself with your own money, you will eventually have to collaborate. Nothing is completely solo. #scriptchat

@P_Hendrickson If you want to write TV, unless you're in the UK, you're always in a writer's room. It's a creative and fun place, alot of work, but more brains to problem solve. You are at the behest of the showrunner and the network, so you will be aiming to enact their vision. #scriptchat

@jeannevb I look for an emotional connection and determine what I can bring creatively to the project. Then I figure out if I'm the right person strategically (I'm too low level so if someone wants to attach me, it may be to access my management team) #scriptchat

@writeranthonydp @jeannevb @Tribeca If a producer option it, then you will probably get attachments first (director, showrunner, actors), then prepare your pitch, then go out and sell it. Try to make sure you have creative say in who gets picked!
@jeannevb @Tribeca COMMUNICATION IS KEY! #scriptchat

@jeannevb @Tribeca I also get the parameters set in our first meeting -- timelines, deadlines, max locations, max characters, budget, the format (my feature was in a 9-act structure for instance) -- and ask if they want things delivered in a certain way & get samples if I can. #scriptchat

@jeannevb @Tribeca I think it's important to find your way into the story. What's the thing that allows you to write it. Once you have a hook in, remember that this idea is someone else's first. I ask what they love about the idea, what they want it to be, so I can accentuate that. #scriptchat

@jeannevb Thanks for the great chats tonight #scriptchat -- great questions from @jeannevb per usual, and wonderful to hear @SadieKDean's take on success/ failure!

@SadieKDean I set goals every year. This year -- develop 2-3 pilots, create 1 new idea/ month, apply for grants, follow up with contacts 2-3x a year.  Stretch goal - write OWA, staffed on show. So far: written 2 pilots, wrote 5 one-pagers, did follow-ups/ applications & staffed. #scriptchat
@JLalliWriter It can happen! It happened to me! #scriptchat

@jeannevb I think it's anything that moves the needle forward. Did I finish something? Did I learn from it? Did it get me reads? Did it get me meetings? Did it get me an interview? Did it get me a job? Did it get optioned? Did it get sold? Did it get made? All successes. #scriptchat

@jeannevb It's important to remember that you have very little control in this business -- except for your own work and how you treat people. Redirect your energy on making those things work, and move on... #scriptchat

@SadieKDean I find that the hardest to do in the moment, but each year, as I take stock of what happened the year before, I can see the needle inching forward. I think it's important, though, to learn to give yourself a break, and celebrate as you go #scriptchat

@jeannevb Failure usually comes when I don't trust my gut or I compromise my values. It's a lesson to always trust my inner voice. Also to bow out when you know it's not working so you can preserve your relationships. #scriptchat

I have asthma so something like COVID could be deadly. That meant I couldn't join him until it was safe. This spiraled us down a path that put us in different countries with a closed border between us -- and we had no idea when we could be together again. 6/6 #covidanniversary

The thing that worried us was that one of John’s direct reports had all the COVID symptoms and tested negative for the flu. We were sure he had it, so John had to quarantine just in case. 5/6 #covidanniversary

At that time, you could only get a COVID test if you were in contact with a confirmed case or if you traveled to China or Italy. John’s colleagues had been in Sweden and came back sick, but they couldn’t get a COVID test – everything was in short supply. 4/6 #covidanniversary
Standing in that bar surrounded by friends and colleagues, I got a text that dropped the bottom out of my world. My husband, John, was potentially exposed to COVID at work. 3/6 #covidanniversary
